<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Anoop Shah (CYS0018)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Anoop</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Shah (CYS0018)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">This statement is written by me in my personal capacity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 28.8pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Sans'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">1. Is cycling safe in towns and cities in the UK?</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Cycling is not safe enough and does not seem safe enough in most </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">towns and cities in the UK. Even though cycling statistics imply that it is reasonably safe, most people are too afraid to cycle on the roads (British Social Attitudes Survey). The Metropolitan Police Commissioner recently said that he would not be prepare</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">d to cycle on London's roads. Most parents would not be prepared to allow their children to cycle on the roads in the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Perception of safety is one of the most important barriers to increasing levels of cycling in the UK, and can only be overcome by sep</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">arating cyclists from motor traffic. This is achieved by building cycle paths along major roads and removing through motor traffic from minor roads, with high quality street design according to the Dutch model.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">For reasons of health, the economy, the envi</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ronment and people's happiness it is essential that cycling is made safer, more convenient and more pleasant in the UK.</span></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 28.8pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Sans'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">2. What central and local Government could do to improve cycling safety</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The Government must implement the recommendations of the All Par</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ty Parliamentary Cycling Group, which was endorsed by parliament but not acted upon.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Some of the key recommendations include 20mph speed limits on all non-trunk roads in urban areas – this is essential for the safety of pedestrians and cyclists. The trans</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">port authority must ensure that the actual speed does not exceed this, using road features to encourage lower speed (e.g. narrow lanes, zebra crossings, speed cameras or speed tables/humps (sinusoidal profile humps across the whole width of the road are pr</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">eferable for cycling). Current </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> criteria require a minimum of three serious injuries or deaths before speed cameras can be installed – </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> is unacceptable; safety systems should be implemented before deaths happen in order to prevent them.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Current roa</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">d design paradigm is to ensure that motor traffic is not delayed, even if this results in inconvenience and danger to cyclists and pedestrians. This leads to high levels of motor vehicle use in the UK, with congestion and pollution. Bow roundabout in Londo</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">n was designed in this way and caused the death of a number of cyclists, because the blue painted superhighway was encroached by left-turning motor vehicles. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> should update the Design Manual for Roads to ensure that high quality walking and cycling ro</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">utes are incorporated in all new road designs. This will reduce reliance on motor cars and the amount of road space they require.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">I recommend that all traffic </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">engineers  go</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> on a Dutch infrastructure study tour in order to see how the system works and lear</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">n from the experts. </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> and other transport organisations should also employ Dutch engineers to ensure that new cycling infrastructure is built correctly. For example, the recently-opened CS2 extension in London, stated by the Mayor to be a high-quality sc</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">heme, has many faults. The only improvement on previous 'superhighways' is that it is segregated from the road by a kerb, but the junctions still have conflicts between cyclists and left-turning vehicles (which should be designed out by separate traffic li</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ghts).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">As well as better road design, there is a need for enforcement of traffic rules with a particular focus on modes of transport which cause the most injuries, i.e. motor vehicles. Sentences for motoring offences need to be reviewed to ensure that dan</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">gerous drivers are removed from the road. Cyclists usually contravene the </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">highway code</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> if the infrastructure is poor, for example they may find it safer to cycle on the footway than on a dangerous road. In such situations this is a sign that the infrastruc</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ture needs to be improved (e.g. by providing a high quality cycle path, to remove the incentive to ride on the footway), rather than reprimanding cyclists.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 28.8pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Sans'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">3. Would be desirable and feasible to segregate cyclists from other road users?</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">It is essential to </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">segregate cyclists from other road users, and the Dutch model of segregation should be used. This is the only way to achieve mass cycling.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">On busy urban roads, separate paths are provided for cyclists, motor vehicles and pedestrians, with segregation at j</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">unctions. This may require the relocation of car parking, removal of motor traffic lanes, </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">removal</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> of grass verges or narrowing of excessively wide footways. Minor roads should not be through roads for motor traffic so that cyclists can share the road with </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">cars. On rural roads where there are few pedestrians, cyclists and pedestrians can share the same path (which should be designed for convenient cycling, of adequate width, with good visibility and free from obstructions).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Emergency measures should be </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">taken along dangerous stretches of road such as the non-segregated part of Cycle Superhighway 2, where temporary barriers can be used to keep motor vehicles out of cycle lanes. Separate left turn signals are required at major intersections to protect cycli</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">sts from left turning traffic. Dangerous </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">lorries</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> with large blind spots should be banned from city centres at busy times.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>